This project implements a Gym Membership and Fitness Class Booking System using core Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) principles in Java.
The goal is to model how gym members book different fitness classes, get charged dynamically, and maintain their account status based on their balance.

ðŸŽ¯ Project Objectives

Apply abstraction, inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation in a realistic scenario.

Design a class hierarchy representing users, fitness classes, and booking behavior.

Demonstrate interface usage and method overriding.

Implement real-world business rules such as:

Dynamic class fees

Weekend discounts

Membership balance validation

| OOP Principle     | How It Is Shown in the Project                                       |
| ----------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Encapsulation** | Member data (balance, ID) hidden behind getters/setters.             |
| **Inheritance**   | All class types inherit from `BookingService`.                       |
| **Polymorphism**  | Child classes override `getFee`, `getDescription`, `chargeFee`.      |
| **Abstraction**   | `BookingService` provides an abstract template for all classes.      |
| **Interfaces**    | `Bookable` ensures all classes are bookable and expose core methods. |



Conclusion

This project successfully implements a modular, maintainable OOP system that models real-world gym class bookings. Through the use of abstract classes, interfaces, inheritance, and encapsulation, the system remains extensibleâ€”new classes can easily be added without changing existing code.

It serves as a complete demonstration of core OOP skills in Java while solving a practical, relatable problem scenario.